This NYT piece and its classroom wrapper make a complex cost‑per‑life‑year comparison accessible to the average reader. It includes data visualization that’s easy for the eye to follow and an expert source. Possible weaknesses include how life‑years were calculated, missing uncertainty ranges, unclear cost breakdowns (like long‑term savings), and confounding in observational Medicaid comparisons, so the headline “cost to save a life” may overstate the study’s precision. 
